"1223","1156":"1156","1210":"1210","1144":"1144","1166":"1166","ABT 1090":"about 1090","1119":"1119","Tir Conaill, Ireland":"County Donegal, Ireland","Ireland":"Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ní","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Jian, Pei-Lin, Kong, Min, Ming, Yung, Bin, Cao, Huang, Jing, Wen, Zhen, Biao, Chang, Chi, Quan, Yaping.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 倪, meaning ‘boundary’ or ‘infants’ in ancient Chinese: adopted in order to escape from a feud in place of the Chinese surname 郳, which is also pronounced Ni. The original surname was from Ni (郳), the name of an ancient state, also called Little Zhu (located in Shandong province), granted to the son of Duke Wu of Zhu (ruler of the state of Zhu, died 796  BC ). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), the name of the state was adopted as a surname.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 賴, see   Lai   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Lai","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Ching, Kwok, Ming, Wing, Wai, Wen, Chi, Chun, Ho, Kam, Man, Yee.  Vietnamese Hung, Thanh, Tuan, Hoa, Ky, Lan, Thang, Tien, Trang, Tu, Yen, Anh.","Chinese: Mandarin or Cantonese form of the surname 賴, meaning ‘depend on’ in Chinese: from Lai (賴), the name of a state (located in Henan province), which was annexed by the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 來, meaning ‘to come’ in Chinese: (i) simplified form of the placename Lai (郲), the name of a fief (located in Henan province) during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). (ii) adopted in place of the Chinese surname Lai (萊) which originated from the name of a fief/state. After its annihilation by the state of Qi, people simplified the name as 萊 in order to escape from political persecutions."]},{"name":"Ny","meanings":["Swedish: ornamental or soldier's name from <i>ny</i> ‘new’. It may sometimes derive from a placename beginning with <i>Ny-</i>.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 倪 (see   Ni  ) or 聶 (see   Nie   2)."]}]},{"name":"Eidin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: relationship name from Middle High German <i>eiden</i> ‘son-in-law’, probably signifying the son-in-law of a person of some importance or fame."],"variants":[{"name":"Eidem","meanings":["German: from Middle High German <i>eidem</i> ‘son-in-law’. See   Eiden  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of various farmsteads in central Norway so named, from Old Norse <i>Eithheimr</i> (<i>eith</i> ‘isthmus’ + <i>heimr</i> ‘farm’)."]}]},{"name":"Dé","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Caillech Dé Ní Eidin was born about 1090, in Ireland as the daughter of Ua hEidin. She had at least 14 sons and 2 daughters with High King Toirdelbach Mór Ua Conchobair of Ireland. She died in 1119, at the age of 30."},"et":{"ABT 1090–1119":"umbes 1090–1119","1090–1119":"1090–1119","1088–1156":"1088–1156","1115–1166":"1115–1166","1126–1144":"1126–1144","1136–1198":"1136–1198","1153–1224":"1153–1224","1156–1181":"1156–1181","–1143":"–1143","–1181":"–1181","–1190":"–1190","–1210":"–1210","–1223":"–1223","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1190":"1190","1090":"1090","1143":"1143","1198":"1198","1088":"1088","1153":"1153","1181":"1181","1115":"1115","1126":"1126","1224":"1224","1136":"1136","1223":"1223","1156":"1156","1210":"1210","1144":"1144","1166":"1166","ABT 1090":"umbes 1090","1119":"1119","Tir Conaill, Ireland":"County Donegal, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa"},"fi":{"ABT 1090–1119":"noin 1090–1119","1090–1119":"1090–1119","1088–1156":"1088–1156","1115–1166":"1115–1166","1126–1144":"1126–1144","1136–1198":"1136–1198","1153–1224":"11